This refactor won’t work in Terraform because the proposed refactor relies on a Terraform pattern that does not work for this kind of hierarchy. A count or for_each resource can create multiple instances, but Terraform does not model dependencies between those instances as an ordered chain; it builds the dependency graph first, and those dependencies are tracked between whole resource blocks rather than “instance 2 depends on instance 1.”

In this case, the suggested pattern would make google_folder.dynamic_folders derive each folder’s parent from another instance of google_folder.dynamic_folders. Although that reads correctly to a person, Terraform interprets it as the resource block depending on itself, which creates a cycle rather than a valid parent-child sequence.

That is why the explicit level_0, level_1, level_2, etc. resources are intentional here. Separate resource blocks let Terraform represent the hierarchy as a valid dependency chain, while a single counted resource cannot safely express “instance N depends on instance N-1” for folder creation.

